I wrote a Rust utility that sends tasks to an API using reqwest. It parses JSON bodies and handles errors. Is there a better way to structure this, maybe with middleware?

fn call_task(payload: &str) -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    let resp = reqwest::get("https://api.example.com/task")?;
    let body = serde_json::from_str::<serde_json::Value>(&payload)?;
    if let Ok(_) = resp.json::<serde_json::Value>().await {}
    Ok(())
}

Rust isn't meant to build full REST servers; it shines as a CLI tool. Your function already does the heavy lifting, and async isn’t needed for sync work. Think of Rust like a hammer—great for tasks but not for assembling furniture.

```rust
fn call_task(payload: &str) -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    let resp = reqwest::get("https://api.example.com/task")?;
    let _body = serde_json::from_str::<serde_json::Value>(&payload)?; // ignore parsed result
    Ok(())
}
```
If you need middleware, consider a higher‑level framework like Actix or Tokio, not raw reqwest in this context.

Think of JWT as a digital passport: it contains claims (user info) signed by the server so the API knows who you are without sending your password each time. The backend verifies the signature, checks the expiry, and extracts the token’s payload.

```rust
fn validate_jwt(token: &str) -> Result<serde_json::Value, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let header = base64::{engine::UrlSafeEncoder}::decode(&token[..len(token)-1])?;
    let payload = base64::{engine::UrlSafeEncoder}::decode(header)?;
    Ok(serde_json::from_str(payload).map_err(|e| Box::new(e)))
}
```
This mirrors the passport‑check process.

You can make parsing optional. Use `from_str` inside a `match` so you return a custom error instead of panicking.

```rust
fn safe_parse<T>(data: &str) -> Result<T, ParseError> where T: serde::DeserializeOwned {
    match serde_json::from_str::<T>(data) {
        Ok(v) => Ok(v),
        Err(e) => Err(ParseError { error: e })
    }
}

#[derive(this::Error)]
error::Type = std::num_traits::TryFromStrError;
#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct ParseError {
    pub error: Box<dyn Error + Send + Sync>,
}

fn process_task(payload: &str) -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    safe_parse::<serde_json::Value>(payload)
        .map_err(|e| ParseError { error: e })
        .map_err(|_| format!("failed to parse task"))
}
```
Analogous to a form where missing fields just show an empty box rather than crashing.

Rust can be as fast or faster because it avoids garbage collection and gives you zero‑cost abstractions, but Go’s runtime overhead is often negligible. For a pure CLI tool like yours, Rust’s memory safety may save a few cycles per request.

```rust
// Example: measuring latency per task
fn measure(pushers: usize) -> f64 {
    let start = std::time::Instant::now();
    for _ in 0..pushers {
        call_task("{\"id\":1}".into());
    }
    (start.elapsed().as_secs_f64() / float64(pushers)).round(3)
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod bench {
    #[test]
    fn rust_perf() { assert!(measure(10_000) < 5.0); }
}
```
If you need async, Tokio gives high throughput; for sync, Rust’s single‑threaded model is predictable.
